# Vercel Speed Insights Installation Report

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the joybox Next.js project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` package (version as per latest npm registry)
- Used npm as the package manager (matching existing project configuration)

### 2. Code Changes
**Modified: `app/layout.js`**
- Added import statement: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next";`
- Integrated `<SpeedInsights />` component in the root layout body
- Followed Next.js App Router pattern as specified in official Vercel documentation

### 3. Updated Files
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
- `package-lock.json` - Updated with new dependency tree
- `app/layout.js` - Added SpeedInsights component integration

## Implementation Details

The implementation followed the official Vercel Speed Insights Quickstart guide (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart) for Next.js App Router projects.

The SpeedInsights component was added to the root layout at `app/layout.js`, placed at the end of the body element to avoid interfering with the page content rendering. This is the recommended approach for Next.js v13.5+ with App Router.

## Verification Steps Completed

✓ Build verification: `npm run build` - Successful
✓ Linter check: `npm run lint` - No new errors introduced (only pre-existing warnings)
✓ Lock file updated: package-lock.json properly reflects new dependency

## Next Steps

To complete the setup:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard for this project
3. Monitor metrics in the Vercel dashboard after deployment and user visits

## Notes
- The project uses Next.js v16.2.4 with App Router
- No breaking changes were introduced
- Existing code structure and styling were preserved
- The SpeedInsights component will automatically start collecting performance metrics once deployed to Vercel
